Cooper's Hawk seen circling about 500' AGL over Hwy 550.  Photos.  Changed to Sharp-shinned as recommended by Julia Plummer:. These photos of a Cooper's Hawk were flagged as being a Sharp-Shinned Hawk by another eBird reviewer. I also consulted a few more regional eBird reviewers because distinguishing these two accipiters is challenging. They mostly agreed that this is a Sharp-shinned Hawk...--The features that point to SSHA include: smallish head with relatively long appearing tail, wings "thrown forward” while soaring, plus the bulging secondaries.

TRIP COMMENTS: I walk this area several times a week.  Leggetts Creek North Scranton has a 3 level echo system. The bottom ATV trail runs along side the creek.  The second level comprised of various bush and Staghorn Suma type shrubs..  The upper top path has a lot of high grass with various trees spread sparingly throughout and several paths that interconnect.  The walk basically starts behind one baseball field and ends at another.  It's not very long, about a 15 minute walk from one end to the other.  You can spend hours cutting up and down to the different levels (as I often do).  Because of the various echo systems, the bird life is very diverse.  At the creek level you'll find Kingfishers, ducks, herons, and just about any other water fowl you can think of depending on the time of year.  Lots of woodpeckers all types.  The middle level you'll have Robins, Bluebirds, Phoebes and the like.  While the upper level is perfect for warbler type birds and many others.  Every raptor bird known loves this place.  Great little hot spot.

TRIP COMMENTS: Darner sp. - 2----Another amazing flight, 299 raptors in just under 5 hours. Sunny, temps soaring to 81F, light SW wind. Conditions began mostly sunny with just a faint haze and scattered clouds. A high layer of patterned clouds arrived at 12:45, then darker cumulus around 2:30. The wind picked up and switched to W as a cold front approached at 3:45, with the front passing through around 4:30. The "Pennsburg Bubble" held true again, with storm cells to our north and south but hardly a drop here. The cell even re-formed after passing us.

Excellent morning tying the property record of 74 species. Sixteen warbler species and multiple property FOYs. I hit maybe ten warbler species right outside the house and up into the upper pasture, and the good luck continued from there. I typically get good diversity and low numbers here (a trade off I would take every time) but there were several pretty good counts today. Just couldn’t get one more species to break the record, there were plenty of common enough birds left on the table.----Addendum: Ended up with 76 species for the day, which I would guess is a new high. Shame the MALL or CEWA didn’t fly over during this list.----Amphibians: American toad (heard), Gray tree frog (heard)----Butterflies: Cabbage white, Clouded sulphur ----Mammals: Coyote (The first or maybe second time that I’ve actually seen one on the property, although I hear them regularly at night through the mic. It was walking along the trail by the creek and came within 20 feet or so of me. We stared at each other for a bit before it slowly trotted off), Eastern cottontail, Eastern gray squirrel
68F, calm to light S wind. Sun initially filtered by some high clouds, then gradually becoming overcast with slow front arriving 4:10 with light rain.----36 raptors in 3.4 hrs, 10.59 birds/hr.

General: There weren't a ton of migrants this morning, but the gamelands were reasonably birdy anyway. The lower/wetland portions had a lot more activity than the upper portion, which was quite dead. PGC had ripped up a ton of brush near the wetland area, turning it into a large brush pile, and lopped the tops off a number of ash trees along Gameland Rd. since my last visit (May 2021 - yeesh).--Route: Parked at the lower lot, did a loop through the wetlands area that eventually (after some unplanned, wet bushwhacking through an overgrown, flooded trail full of multiflora rose) wound up dumping me into the back end of the game commission maintenance area. Walked south on Gameland Rd. from here, crossing Ridge Valley Rd., and covered a chunk of the southern area of this SGL. A couple of hunters were setting up tree stands down here. Some of the paths had not been mowed recently. After wrapping up here, I walked back up to the lower parking lot, got in my car and drove to the upper parking lot at 5-10mph. Did a loop from this lot which involved me walking south along the recently cleared gas line cut back to Gameland Rd. 3.28 miles were recorded by the app including backtracking.--Weather: High 50s F rising to near 70F. Sunny, calm wind.--Non-bird: 1 Eastern Chipmunk (heard), 2 Spring Peepers (heard), Monarch.

TRIP COMMENTS: General: Decided to bird this SGL while my wife and mother-in-law visited the Endless Mountains Fiber Festival in nearby New Milford.--Route: Parked at the lot at 41.88696, -75.75227 and hiked a service road up the steep hill on the opposite/south side of the road. Eventually, the path turned 90 degrees to the northeast and leveled off. I followed this path until eventually turning around at a set of red blazes. After backtracking all the way down the hill, I walked School Rd. to Gamelands Rd., then took Gamelands out to the parking lot at 41.89237, -75.75329, which seemed like a convenient turnaround spot. (It was along Gamelands where I hit the biggest/best mixed flock of the afternoon. There were some nice pockets of activity at the top of the hill too. Dead zones between all of them. Talking 5+ minutes between birds dead zones.) On the walk back to my car, I poked my nose into the southernmost of the food plot areas on the east side of Gamelands Rd. (Clover planting, evidently.) Nothing was active there, and I was feeling dehydrated, so I didn't bother exploring that area any further. 2.98 miles was recorded by the app, including backtracking.--Non-bird: 4 American Red Squirrels, 1 Eastern Gray Squirrel, 2 Eastern Chipmunks (heard), 3 Spring Peepers (heard).

TRIP COMMENTS: This was a fascinating observation. I initially spotted a female kestrel perched on a power line along the south side of the street, then noticed two birds perched on another power line on the north side. Turned out to be another female kestrel perched about five feet from a sharp-shinned hawk in a seemingly amicable situation. After about a half minute the SSHA took off, circled around, and buzzed the kestrel (who didn’t react)  before flying across the field where it was joined by a third kestrel, and the two did a little aerial jousting before the SSHA returned to the wire and perched only about two feet from the female kestrel it was previously near. Eventually the two of them took off together and did some half-hearted swooping and chasing before the SSHA flew into some pine trees. A fourth kestrel appeared from that vicinity shortly after; all four kestrels were observed perched around the field at the same time.

Event: October Big Day (yardbirding).--General: Big Sit-esque, but I moved around a bit more than the rules allow. Few flyovers were noted. Scott Godshall, a mile away, mentioned seeing a bunch of Accipiters and falcons over his place, but I was really struggling to get eyes on any raptors at all. The yard's Oct warbler species high count, 8, set only a few days ago, was handily topped by today's haul of 11. Would've been 12 if I could've scrounged up a Common Yellowthroat - usually one of the easier warblers in the yard. I was actually finding myself feeling disappointed when the Tennessee Warbler kept popping up in the goldenrod, hoping that it a yellowthroat.--Weather: High 40s to low 50s F, sunny, ~10mph cool northwest breeze.--Non-bird: 3 Eastern Gray Squirrels, 2 Eastern Chipmunks, 1 Green Frog.

Property Big Sit year 4.  Total species count was 52.  Last year's count was 48 species.  Fairly productive but I was hoping for more given the favorable NW winds and the Birdcast migration indicating there would be a good nocturnal movement.  NFC results were underwhelming.  This was the coldest Big Sit I can remember, even in the afternoon I was only comfortable when I moved into the sun.  I had a nice variety of raptors but really struck out on warblers.----Seven new birds were added to the Big Sit bringing the cumulative total up to 75.  Also added one new mammal to the count.----New birds added to the count: Red-shouldered hawk, Peregrine falcon, Tree swallow, House wren, Gray catbird, Dark-eyed junco, Common yellowthroat----Weather: Partly cloudy to start but quickly clearing. 48F rising to 55F.  Winds NW at 3-10 mph. One shooting star.----Butterflies: Cabbage white 2, Monarch (2 - high and headed south)----Mammals: Eastern cottontail (new for the Big Sit), Eastern gray squirrel 2

LOCALITY: 2678 Summer Valley Road, New Ringgold, Pennsylvania, US (40.691, -75.934)

TRIP COMMENTS: General: Round 2 of Hammond's Flycatcher chase. I was relaxing in my car in a Tuscarora SP parking lot, after eating a late lunch, when a phonecall from Mike Lyman alerted me that the bird had finally been seen. Of course, it was gone by the time I could hike out there. And then another person caught a glimpse of it another hour or so later. As I was in the process of giving up at sunset, it finally appeared. I'd literally said "I give up" moments before it appeared, as if summoned by me throwing in the towel. --Route: Same as the morning: parked at the boat launch, walked east along the shore to the dam breast area, where the flycatcher had been hanging out. 1.39 miles recorded by app, including backtracking.--Non-bird: 2 Eastern Chipmunks, large blue dragonfly.--Others: A few other Hammond's hunters were out by this point, including Mike Lyman and Debbie Beer.
